<br>
The fact is, lowering the mana cost as you suggest, lowering the casting cost and aggro as I've said over and over and over again would accomplish the same thing without requiring gear.  Casters use spells to do their duty, adding in a new line of wands and such (stock in trade of ANY rpg but EQ's attempt at being one) would require not only additional work and addition to the game with drops and such, but change the entire paradigm the game is designed around.<br>
<br>
What paradigm is this?  Casters use spells and abilities, melee uses equipment.  The game is basically structured around this.  Yes, melee now shares our abilities and spells in items and has free disciplines, and we have to have certain gear to survive and compete so its been muddied (mostly in melee side) but the situation still stands.<br>
<br>
Fix our spells and we'll do what we should.  Require gear and SOME of us will have a shot at maybe doing what we should - at a price the melee doesn't have to pay.  Remember there's three reasons we can't just rip out the damage already and that's mana, time, and aggro.  Fix THOSE problems, and you have wizards functioning better.<br>
<br>
That was the whole point of my &quot;why do Wizards do well on raids&quot; thread - to show that what makes Wizards liked and powerful on raids is what could be done to make them better in normal hunting.  What was proved and demonstrated over and over in that thread was just what I said above. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uetnu.showPublicProfile?language=EN>etnu</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br>  Posts: 1087<br> <font color=#ffffff>(1/3/02 8:11 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: gear and balance.</span><hr size=1> Grimm, if caster items were upgraded AS A WHOLE (i.e. every commonly used main hand item has a useful effect / mana regen bonus on it) it would effectively work the same way as melee items do.<br>
